<text xml:lang="ta">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <p xml:id="PN260-intro">tiṇai, atu; tuṟai, kaiyaṟunilai pāṇpāṭṭumām<gap quantity="4" reason="lost" unit="character"/> vaṭamōtaṅkiḻār pāṭiyatu.
      </p>
      <p xml:lang="en">  
      </p>
    </div>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="PN260">
<l>vaḷarat toṭiṉum vauvupu tirintu</l>
<l>viḷari yuṟutarun tīntoṭai niṉaiyāt</l>
<l>taḷaru neñcan talaii maṉaiyō</l>
<l>ḷuḷaruṅ kūnta ṉōkkik kaḷara</l>
<l>kaḷḷi nīḻaṟ kaṭavuḷ vāḻttip</l>
<l>pacipaṭu maruṅkulai kacipukai toḻāak</l>
<l>kāṇaleṉ kolleṉa viṉaviṉai varūum</l>
<l>pāṇa kēṇmati yāṇaratu nilaiyē</l>
<l>puravuttoṭut tuṇkuvai yāyiṉu miravuveḻun</l>
<l>tevvaṅ koḷkuvai yāyiṉu miraṇṭuṅ</l>
<l>kaiyuḷa pōluṅ kaṭitaṇ maiyavē</l>
<l>muṉṉūrp pūcaliṟ ṟōṉṟit taṉṉūr</l>
<l>neṭunirai taḻīiya mīḷi yāḷar</l>
<l>viṭukaṇai nīttan tuṭipuṇai yāka</l>
<l>veṉṟi tantu koṉṟukōḷ viṭuttu</l>
<l>vaiyakam pulampa vaḷaiiya pāmpiṉ</l>
<l>vaiyeyiṟ ṟuynta matiyiṉ maṟavar</l>
<l>kaiyakat tuynta kaṉṟuṭaip pallā</l>
<l>ṉiraiyoṭu vanta vuraiya ṉāki</l>
<l>yurikaḷai yarava māṉat tāṉē</l>
<l>yarituce lulakiṟ ceṉṟaṉa ṉuṭampē</l>
<l>kāṉac ciṟṟiyāṟ ṟaruṅkaraik kāluṟṟuk</l>
<l>kampamoṭu tuḷaṅkiya vilakkam pōla</l>
<l>vampoṭu tuḷaṅki yāṇṭoḻin taṉṟē</l>
<l>yuyaricai veṟuppat tōṉṟiya peyarē</l>
<l>maṭañcāṉ maññai yaṇimayir cūṭṭi</l>
<l>yiṭampiṟar koḷḷāc ciṟuvaḻip</l>
<l>paṭañcey pantark kaṉmicai yatuvē.</l>
</lg>
<lg xml:lang="en">
<l corresp="2">Thinking of the sweet strings tuned in Viḷari </l>
<l corresp="1">after touching [them] so that [the note?] grows, gripping [and] swerving, </l>
<l corresp="3a-c">offering [your] weary heart, looking at </l>
<l>the ruffled tresses of the lady of the house, praising</l>
<l corresp="3d-5">the deity in the shade of the salt-ground[-grown] spurge, </l>
<l corresp="6">you with a waist that has experienced hunger, compassionate, folding [your] hands, </l>
<l corresp="7-8a">o bard who comes asking “do I not see [him]?”, </l>
<l corresp="8b-d">listen [what is] the state of [our] prosperity: </l>
<l corresp="9">Whether you eat, taking on a boon [or] whether you rise for begging </l>
<l corresp="10">[and] accept misery, just two </l>
<l corresp="11">actions exist, it seems, that are quickly at hand. </l>
<l corresp="19cd">	Being one of [his] word who, </l>
<l>after appearing in the skirmish at the village in front, bringing victory,</l>
<l>with the Tuṭi drum as a support, in the flood of arrows</l>
<l>sent out by the commanding men who had enveloped the large herd</l>
<l corresp="12-15">of his village, killing, setting free the catch (~ the cows stolen by those men), </l>
<l corresp="19ab">came [back] with the herds </l>
<l corresp="18">of many calf-possessing cows that had escaped from the hands </l>
<l corresp="17">of bold men like the moon that escapes from the sharp teeth </l>
<l corresp="16">of the snake that had encircled [it] so that the world lamented, </l>
<l corresp="20">he himself, like the snake that sheds [its] skin, </l>
<l corresp="21">has gone to the world difficult to go to. [His] body, </l>
<l corresp="22">catching [his] foot on the difficult shore of the little forest river, </l>
<l corresp="23">like the target that sways with [its] pole, </l>
<l corresp="24">swaying with arrows it has remained behind there. </l>
<l corresp="25">[His] name that appeared much in high fame, </l>
<l corresp="26">wearing as a decoration the feathers of a youthful peacock </l>
<l corresp="28">it is [now] on a stone, with a shade made of cloth, </l>
<l corresp="27">on the little way not taken by strangers to [this] place. </l>
</lg>
